Attempts to institute a new international sugar agreement
to stabilize sugar prices are being made in Geneva. Convened
by the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development
on September 12, the three-week meeting is a follow-up to a
session held in the spring of '77 which ended in deadlock.
U.S. officials have called for the creation of a reserve of 3
million tons and are relatively optimistic that an agreement
will be reached on stocks and quotas, says the UPI. "Such
stocks," says conference chairman Ernest Jones-Perry,
"should be financed by both exporting and importing mem-
bers of the organization with fees of up to half a cent a pound
to establish a sugar stabilization fund."
